When compiling main.c, the compliler processes the file from top to bottom.
if it encounters the add(5,7) function call, without knowing add, i will throw out
an error,since the function's signature is unkown. The extern keyword is used 
to disregard the unknown signature hoping the linker will find the function.

By separation compilation it is only necessary to recomplie the specific .c files 
that changed into new .o. The unchanged .o files can be reused when linking. 
This is especially usfull in larger codebases.

Both single command and manual linking compile to the same temporary 
object file and link them under the hood. single command hides this 
process and discards the object file afterwards. Manual linking seperates
this steps.
